{"type": "assistant", "message": {"model": "claude-sonnet-4-6", "id": "msg_vrtx_01P5VuxHux3TstJVe6hrPRpn", "type": "message", "role": "assistant", "content": [{"type": "thinking", "thinking": "Now I have the full picture. The ValidatingAdmissionPolicy is clear: ALL custom MachineConfigPools (non-master/worker/arbiter) **must** inherit from the worker pool. The policy enforces this at the API level with `failurePolicy: Fail`, meaning it will actively reject any CREATE or UPDATE that doesn't comply.\n\nSpecifically, a custom pool's `machineConfigSelector` must use **either**:\n1. `matchLabels` with `machineconfiguration.openshift.io/role` set to `master`, `worker`, or `arbiter` (built-in pools only)\n2. `matchExpressions` with an `In` operator that includes `worker` in its values, or a `NotIn` operator that doesn't exclude `worker`\n\nThe user's request to create a selector that only matches `infra-custom` without any worker inheritance would be rejected by this policy. I need to explain that this specific configuration is blocked at the API level.\n\nThe workaround would be using a `matchExpressions` with `In` operator listing both `worker` and `infra`, but that still pulls in worker configurations \u2014 exactly what the user wants to avoid. I'm re-examining the `NotIn` condition in the VAP to understand if there's another path forward, but the logic seems to require that `worker` either appears in an `In` expression or is absent from a `NotIn` expression, which doesn't give the user the isolation they're looking for. So the validation rule checks that if a NotIn expression exists for the role key, \"worker\" must not be in its values list. This means you can't use NotIn to exclude worker, effectively ensuring worker configs are always potentially matched. Combined with the failurePolicy set to Fail, the VAP prevents creating any custom MCP that doesn't inherit from worker\u2014it's enforced at the API level.\n\nThe user's goal of having a completely separate selector isn't achievable with the standard MCO setup. I should explain this constraint clearly and show them what they can actually do instead: use `In: [worker, infra]` with a custom label like `infra-custom` for their specific configs, while accepting that worker baseline configs will also apply.", "signature": ""}], "stop_reason": null, "stop_sequence": null, "stop_details": null, "usage": {"input_tokens": 1, "cache_creation_input_tokens": 858, "cache_read_input_tokens": 36196, "cache_creation": {"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens": 858, "ephemeral_1h_input_tokens": 0}, "output_tokens": 10}, "context_management": null}, "parent_tool_use_id": null, "session_id": "2fe54bd0-271e-4b69-992f-525b199bb078", "uuid": "86099a6d-8456-4ee5-b57a-0081cc13ea11", "request_id": "req_vrtx_011CcK12DU9rneP2rs4T8iX5", "timestamp": "2026-06-22T21:23:19.434Z"}
{"type": "assistant", "message": {"model": "claude-sonnet-4-6", "id": "msg_vrtx_01P5VuxHux3TstJVe6hrPRpn", "type": "message", "role": "assistant", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "What you're asking for is **blocked at the API level** by a `ValidatingAdmissionPolicy` that MCO ships (line 18-42 of the file above). Here's exactly what it enforces and what you can actually do.\n\n---\n\n## The Constraint\n\nThe VAP (`custom-machine-config-pool-selector`) runs on every `CREATE`/`UPDATE` of a `MachineConfigPool` with `failurePolicy: Fail`. It rejects any custom pool whose `machineConfigSelector` does **not** meet one of these conditions:\n\n1. `matchLabels` with role `master`, `worker`, or `arbiter` \u2014 reserved for built-in pools only\n2. `matchExpressions` with an `In` expression that **includes `worker`** in values\n3. `matchExpressions` with a `NotIn` expression where `worker` is **not** in the exclusion list\n\nThis means a standalone `matchLabels: role: infra-custom` (your goal) is **explicitly rejected**. The policy message makes the intent clear:\n\n> *\"All custom MachineConfigPools must inherit from the worker pool and must have a machineConfigSelector that matches for a `machineconfiguration.openshift.io/role: worker` label\"*\n\n---\n\n## What You Can Do\n\nThe supported pattern for a custom infra pool is:\n\n```yaml\napiVersion: machineconfiguration.openshift.io/v1\nkind: MachineConfigPool\nmetadata:\n  name: infra\nspec:\n  machineConfigSelector:\n    matchExpressions:\n      - key: machineconfiguration.openshift.io/role\n        operator: In\n        values:\n          - worker\n          - infra          # or your custom role name\n  nodeSelector:\n    matchLabels:\n      node-role.kubernetes.io/infra: \"\"\n```\n\nYour infra-specific `MachineConfig` objects get labeled:\n\n```yaml\nmetadata:\n  labels:\n    machineconfiguration.openshift.io/role: infra\n```\n\nAnd worker-baseline configs (labeled `role: worker`) are **also picked up** \u2014 that's the mandatory inheritance. Your infra configs layer on top of the worker base.\n\n---\n\n## Why MCO Requires This\n\nThe render controller (`pkg/controller/render/render_controller.go`) merges all matched MachineConfigs by name order. Without the worker base, infra nodes would lack the OS configuration that MCO relies on (Ignition base, CRI-O, kubelet, etc.). Allowing a fully isolated pool would produce nodes that diverge from a known-good base in ways MCO can't safely manage.\n\n---\n\n**Bottom line:** a completely worker-independent selector is not achievable in stock MCO \u2014 the VAP actively rejects it on every API call. Use `In: [worker, infra]` and use the `infra` role label exclusively on your infra-specific configs to keep your customizations cleanly separated from the worker baseline."}], "stop_reason": null, "stop_sequence": null, "stop_details": null, "usage": {"input_tokens": 1, "cache_creation_input_tokens": 858, "cache_read_input_tokens": 36196, "cache_creation": {"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens": 858, "ephemeral_1h_input_tokens": 0}, "output_tokens": 10}, "context_management": null}, "parent_tool_use_id": null, "session_id": "2fe54bd0-271e-4b69-992f-525b199bb078", "uuid": "ae337a16-f295-4916-b356-257b514656a3", "request_id": "req_vrtx_011CcK12DU9rneP2rs4T8iX5", "timestamp": "2026-06-22T21:23:31.077Z"}
